an equipment of rights, is "adequate notice" and "fair hearing,"
1 expensive this area, because it
is the topic of current campus discussion and because I believe that
individual claims to have adequate
notice and fair hearing should be
respected and protected in college governmental operations.
Among other essentials, “the right
to a hearing emirates not only
the right to present evidence but
also a reasonable opportunity to
know the claims of the opposite
party and to meet them,” (304 U.S.
18.)
In constitutional cases involving
standards of fair hearing. courts
are frequently troubled by money<
very and problems attending the
ability and effort of one party to
prevent or supplies evidence useful to the other party. in courts of
law, the individual has many liabilities (or restrictions of freedom),
such as subpoena, path, and con<
tampa liability, as well as certain
safeguards, relevant to this problem of prevention or compression of
evidence. These liabilities are not
typical of hearings on the college
