The FCSA
We don’t quite understand why the faculty, through the
Faculty Committee on Student Affairs, has taken upon itself
to administer law and order on the Grinnell campus.
What profiles us most is that, unlike administration officials, we can’t even talk to the FCSA. To be sure, we did
receive a value written statement on the committee‘s duties
that appeared in the first issue of the 5&3 after Christmas,
but we have never been granted an interview.
To weighted our irrigation, in its most recent statement
the FCSA observed that its lninutes show that the committee
had indeed made a recommendation on the problem of ju 'function at a January meeting and that the problem was discussed at other meetings Then the report plants the students:
“Student insurance of this fact does not excuse the charges
that have been made against the committee.”
Still, the FCSA has consistently refused to discuss
the business of its meetings with the 5&3.
Our records show that three of the eight FCSA members
do not subscribe to the 8&8, which does at least give an indication of present campus attitudes. Are not the non-subscribers failing to inform themselves of Student Affairs, even
though such information is easily available?
Finally, we just cannon see why any faculty member
would want to get involved in an advertising that adds so
greatly to a schedule that apparently has most processors
teaching too many classes.
So let’s give up on the FCSA and give back to the administration that which the administration says it processes—
the right to judge student conduct. The actions of the administration, at least, are understandable, even if not agreed with,
