Approximately 100 of 132 senior
men have so far failed to complete
the physical education objectives
required for graduation.
According to John deutsch (physical education), only five or six
Out of the 100 are "in jeopardy of
not graduation."
deutsch said that the vast ma«
jority of the men have completed
art of the physical education oh-
drives which qualify for two academic credits and are needed for
graduation.
The present senior class at Grinlies is the first to graduate under
the revised physical education requirement institutes in the fall
If 1561.
To pass physical education, seniors must (1) pass the college
lwimmmg test, (2) demonstrate
Iliill in two individual hardcover
sports, (3) pass a physical fitness
list, and (4) participate in team
sports.
“The situation inn‘t really as
bad as it looks,” deutsch said. He
has checked each student's progress, and said that all are within
ﬂanne.
 
"There inn’t anybody who dress‘t feel he can complete the requirements,” he said.
Looking at the individual requirements within the program,
deutsch said that there are only
two seniors who have had to resort to classes this semester to
complete their team sport requirement. Normally, the team sport
requirement is satisfied by participation in at least four intramural sports.
deutsch said some men have not
yet passed the swimming test, but
only three or four can’t swim. The
others are people who haven’t
taken the test yet. He said there
inn’t anyone Who will find it im»
possible to complete the swimming
requirement.
According to deutsch, five or six
men have not completed the physical fitness portion of the test.
Most of the 100 men who have
not completed their physical education requirement back either a
major or a minor hardcover
sport, said deutsch. He added, “The
great majority or these have done
work in one or both carry-over
sports. Looking fairly closely at
the situation, I think it's going to
be okay."
 
deutsch said he was most concerned about the four to six men
“who've chosen to procrastinate."
In their cases, few of the physical
education requirements have been
completed and their graduation is
doubtful.
As to the program itself, deutsch
feels that it has been successful.
He bald, “I think the people I
have worked with have gotten
more from this program than the
aid program." The old program
applied to the class of 1964.
The worst calendars in failing to
complete the requirements, said
deutsch, are the variety athletes.
Offered for men as motors are
the following sports: tennis, golf,
athletics, small Craft, bowling,
and garage. For motors the same
sports are offered, and in addition, bndmiton, middle tennis,
funding, riding, skiing, ice skating,
and unicycling can be taken for
credit.
